<paragraph blockId="36.[189,885,1865,1891]" box="[189,885,1865,1891]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
For synonymy and a description, refer to 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuchert P." box="[675,881,1865,1891]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref26517" refString="Schuchert P. 1997. Review of the family Halopterididae. Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden 309: 1 - 162. Available from https: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 149017 [accessed 12 Aug. 2020]." type="journal article" year="1997">Schuchert (1997)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="36.[189,1398,1930,2027]" lastBlockId="37.[189,1399,267,576]" lastPageId="37" lastPageNumber="38" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
In the present material, the lateral nematothecae associated to the cauline hydrothecae on the side opposite to the cladial apophyses are often absent (
<figureCitation box="[681,790,1965,1992]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="31.[190,233,1684,1710]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[229,1357,259,2022]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Fig. 14 (opposite page). A–D. Corhiza patula Galea sp. nov., from holotype MNHN-IK-2015-602, proximal portion of cladium (A); nematothecae: mesial (B), lateral (C), and from ahydrothecate internode (D). — E–J. Corhiza pauciarmata Ansín Agís et al., 2009, from sample MNHN-IK-2015-604, portion of cladium (E); nematothecae: mesial (F), lateral (G) and from ahydrothecate internode in lateral (H) and adaxial (I) aspects; cnidome (J). — K. Halopteris campanula (Busk, 1852), portion of cladium from sample MNHN-IK-2015-597. — L–M. Halopteris infundibulum Vervoort, 1966, cladial hydrotheca in lateral (L) and frontal (M) aspects, both from sample MNHN-IK-2015-608. — N–P. Halopteris peculiaris Billard, 1913, proximal portion of cladium seen laterally (N); single (O) or paired (P) lateral nematothecae associated to cauline hydrothecae; all from sample MNHN-IK-2015-609. Scale bars: A, E = 500 µm; B–D, F–I, O–P = 100 µm; J = 10 µm; K–N = 300 µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4012153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4012153/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 14O</figureCitation>
); in only rare instances, a pair is formed (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1385,1965,1992]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="31.[190,233,1684,1710]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[229,1357,259,2022]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Fig. 14 (opposite page). A–D. Corhiza patula Galea sp. nov., from holotype MNHN-IK-2015-602, proximal portion of cladium (A); nematothecae: mesial (B), lateral (C), and from ahydrothecate internode (D). — E–J. Corhiza pauciarmata Ansín Agís et al., 2009, from sample MNHN-IK-2015-604, portion of cladium (E); nematothecae: mesial (F), lateral (G) and from ahydrothecate internode in lateral (H) and adaxial (I) aspects; cnidome (J). — K. Halopteris campanula (Busk, 1852), portion of cladium from sample MNHN-IK-2015-597. — L–M. Halopteris infundibulum Vervoort, 1966, cladial hydrotheca in lateral (L) and frontal (M) aspects, both from sample MNHN-IK-2015-608. — N–P. Halopteris peculiaris Billard, 1913, proximal portion of cladium seen laterally (N); single (O) or paired (P) lateral nematothecae associated to cauline hydrothecae; all from sample MNHN-IK-2015-609. Scale bars: A, E = 500 µm; B–D, F–I, O–P = 100 µm; J = 10 µm; K–N = 300 µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4012153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4012153/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 14P</figureCitation>
). The cladia display a regular structure: they begin with a short, quadrangular, athecate segment, followed by an ahydrothecate internode bearing a superior nematotheca and ending distally in an oblique node; afterwards, the segmentation is heteromerous, with up to 8 hydrothecate internode alternating with ahydrothecate counterparts (
<figureCitation box="[526,636,338,364]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="31.[190,233,1684,1710]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[229,1357,259,2022]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Fig. 14 (opposite page). A–D. Corhiza patula Galea sp. nov., from holotype MNHN-IK-2015-602, proximal portion of cladium (A); nematothecae: mesial (B), lateral (C), and from ahydrothecate internode (D). — E–J. Corhiza pauciarmata Ansín Agís et al., 2009, from sample MNHN-IK-2015-604, portion of cladium (E); nematothecae: mesial (F), lateral (G) and from ahydrothecate internode in lateral (H) and adaxial (I) aspects; cnidome (J). — K. Halopteris campanula (Busk, 1852), portion of cladium from sample MNHN-IK-2015-597. — L–M. Halopteris infundibulum Vervoort, 1966, cladial hydrotheca in lateral (L) and frontal (M) aspects, both from sample MNHN-IK-2015-608. — N–P. Halopteris peculiaris Billard, 1913, proximal portion of cladium seen laterally (N); single (O) or paired (P) lateral nematothecae associated to cauline hydrothecae; all from sample MNHN-IK-2015-609. Scale bars: A, E = 500 µm; B–D, F–I, O–P = 100 µm; J = 10 µm; K–N = 300 µm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4012153" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4012153/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 14N</figureCitation>
); the latter are short, delimited proximally by a transverse node and distally by an oblique node, and bear a frontal nematotheca; the hydrothecate internodes are slightly longer, are delimited proximally by an oblique node and distally by a transverse one, and bear distally a hydrotheca and its 4 associated nematothecae: a mesial, a pair of laterals, and a scale-shaped axillar one. There is an important sexual dimorphism of the gonothecae: the female, given off from below the cauline hydrothecae, are large, ovoid and bear proximally 3 nematothecae (
<figureCitation box="[1156,1269,514,541]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="35.[189,232,1860,1886]" captionTargetBox="[193,1394,1137,1812]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[189,1398,1131,1814]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="Fig. 15. A–B. Halopteris campanula (Busk, 1852), female (A) and male (B) gonothecae from samples MNHN-IK-2015-598 and MNHN-IK-2015-597, respectively. — C. Halopteris infundibulum Vervoort, 1966, possible female gonotheca, from sample MNHN-IK-2015-608. — D–E. Halopteris peculiaris Billard, 1913, female (D) and male (E) gonothecae, both from sample MNHN-IK-2015-609. Scale bar: 300 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4011083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4011083/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 15D</figureCitation>
); the male gonothecae, borne on cladia, are comparatively minute, and bear a single basal gonotheca (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1362,549,576]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="35.[189,232,1860,1886]" captionTargetBox="[193,1394,1137,1812]" captionTargetId="figure@35.[189,1398,1131,1814]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="Fig. 15. A–B. Halopteris campanula (Busk, 1852), female (A) and male (B) gonothecae from samples MNHN-IK-2015-598 and MNHN-IK-2015-597, respectively. — C. Halopteris infundibulum Vervoort, 1966, possible female gonotheca, from sample MNHN-IK-2015-608. — D–E. Halopteris peculiaris Billard, 1913, female (D) and male (E) gonothecae, both from sample MNHN-IK-2015-609. Scale bar: 300 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4011083" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4011083/files/figure.png" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Fig. 15E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
